                <h3 class="subheading">Chassis and Dynamics: Built for Agility</h3>
                <p>To earn the name "Scrambler," a bike needs to be light, agile, and able to take a beating. The Scrambler 450 is expected to use a variation of the new twin-spar frame that underpins the Himalayan 450, but with geometry tweaks to make it more road-friendly.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Suspension: </span>This is where the Scrambler character shines. It is widely anticipated to feature<span class="font-weight-700"> Upside-Down (USD) front forks</span> for superior handling and stability, coupled with a rear mono-shock with linkage. The suspension travel is expected to be generous but less than the Himalayan 450, likely around 180 mm to 190 mm for the front and 180 mm for the rear. This setup perfectly balances on-road precision with enough travel to absorb unexpected potholes and tackle unpaved trails.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Braking: </span>Dual-channel Anti-lock Braking System (ABS) is a given, but a crucial Scrambler feature is expected to be <span class="font-weight-700">Switchable ABS for the rear wheel. </span>This allows experienced riders to lock the rear wheel for off-road slides and greater control on loose surfaces. The front disc will likely be a large 320 mm unit for strong stopping power.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Weight: </span>One of the most significant factors will be the kerb weight. To compete effectively and feel nimble, the Scrambler 450 is expected to be lighter than the Himalayan 450, potentially tipping the scales at around 185 kg.</li>
                </ul>
                <h3 class="subheading">Technology and Features: Stepping into the Future</h3>
                <p>Royal Enfield has been rapidly modernising its lineup, and the Scrambler 450 is expected to benefit from all the latest advancements, creating a compelling package for the tech-savvy rider.</p>
